1
00:00:29,880 --> 00:00:31,800
You patched things up
with him yet?

2
00:00:32,200 --> 00:00:34,720
Sounds like he's cut you
out of his life.

3
00:00:35,050 --> 00:00:35,890
Forget it.

4
00:00:35,910 --> 00:00:39,160
You told me things can't go back
to the way they were.

5
00:00:39,920 --> 00:00:44,810
"Guys, 'Between Us in
the Deep Forest' is blowing up."

6
00:00:44,810 --> 00:00:46,760
"Y for Life: Review"
I completely lost my mind.

7
00:00:46,760 --> 00:00:49,880
"Men on an untamed forest trek,"

8
00:00:49,880 --> 00:00:52,720
"sparse steamy scenes,"

9
00:00:52,720 --> 00:00:55,160
"just friendship
taking full center stage."

10
00:00:55,160 --> 00:00:56,800
"I'm seven chapters in now"

11
00:00:56,800 --> 00:00:59,320
"and the leads haven't kissed once."

12
00:00:59,320 --> 00:01:02,400
But just one look between them
and I'm already gone.

13
00:01:02,400 --> 00:01:06,240
The writing style is
full-on old school.

14
00:01:06,240 --> 00:01:08,640
Like vintage novels
from the classic era.

15
00:01:08,640 --> 00:01:10,280
Some words had me
doing double takes.

16
00:01:10,280 --> 00:01:13,200
I looked them up
and got completely floored.

17
00:01:13,200 --> 00:01:15,720
So deep. Actual tears.

18
00:01:15,720 --> 00:01:18,800
Need that pleasure hit?
This book has it.

19
00:01:18,800 --> 00:01:22,640
"Between Us in the Deep Forest"
is still free. Why wait?

20
00:01:22,640 --> 00:01:26,560
Dive in before you have to
pay to read it.

21
00:01:26,560 --> 00:01:28,080
Do it today.

22
00:01:28,360 --> 00:01:31,120
Mabel, don't scroll yet.
I can't keep up.

23
00:01:31,520 --> 00:01:32,640
Okay, okay.

24
00:01:35,640 --> 00:01:37,640
What's "gaw-pon" (comprise) anyway?

25
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:39,320
Did Grandpa misspell it?

26
00:01:44,440 --> 00:01:45,760
No, not "gaw-pon."

27
00:01:45,760 --> 00:01:48,360
It reads "gop."
He didn't misspell it.

28
00:01:48,360 --> 00:01:50,720
It's short for "prakob." (comprise)
Get it?

29
00:01:51,020 --> 00:01:52,920
- Hmm?...Really?
- Mm-hmm.

30
00:01:52,920 --> 00:01:54,280
Never heard that before.

31
00:01:54,760 --> 00:01:58,120
Sure you have. It's in
the wai kru (teacher homage) chant.

32
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:03,420
(Sings in saraphanya melody)
Phu gop gerd bpra-yote suk-sa

33
00:02:03,790 --> 00:02:05,800
Wow, old school.

34
00:02:06,320 --> 00:02:07,560
Ahem.

35
00:02:09,520 --> 00:02:11,000
Did you just call me old?

36
00:02:12,240 --> 00:02:15,480
You lot live as long as I have,
then we'll talk.

37
00:02:15,750 --> 00:02:20,760
You know these words
all come from my era?

38
00:02:22,720 --> 00:02:26,920
Grandpa, everyone online is
hunting down Honey Cheese Pie now.

39
00:02:26,920 --> 00:02:29,200
What on earth is Honey Cheese Pie?

40
00:02:30,040 --> 00:02:31,280
Your pen name, Grandpa.

41
00:02:31,280 --> 00:02:33,800
Ugh, that gives me a toothache.

42
00:02:33,960 --> 00:02:36,920
Since when did I end up
with such a sugary name?

43
00:02:38,120 --> 00:02:40,720
Since I posted your novel online.

44
00:02:40,970 --> 00:02:41,750
What?

45
00:02:41,950 --> 00:02:47,120
Honey Cheese Pie,
that's the pen name I gave you.

46
00:02:47,120 --> 00:02:48,120
What?

47
00:02:48,840 --> 00:02:51,490
It's a riff on Harn Chanprai.
Works, right?

48
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:53,240
Works for you maybe.

49
00:02:53,240 --> 00:02:56,080
Next time ask first.

50
00:02:56,360 --> 00:02:59,480
Come on, Grandpa.
You said anything was fine.

51
00:02:59,480 --> 00:03:00,840
Heh...anything's fine?

52
00:03:00,970 --> 00:03:04,440
How about from now on
you're Dog not Save?

53
00:03:04,650 --> 00:03:05,440
Haha.

54
00:03:05,460 --> 00:03:07,460
- Awoo.
- Awoo.

55
00:03:08,050 --> 00:03:10,960
Honey Cheese Pie is my name.

56
00:03:12,120 --> 00:03:12,970
Awoo.

57
00:03:14,550 --> 00:03:16,600
Celebrating 600,000 views.

58
00:03:16,600 --> 00:03:20,560
- Cheers...
- Cheers...

59
00:03:23,060 --> 00:03:24,720
Here, want some snacks, kids?

60
00:03:25,380 --> 00:03:27,040
This is amazing, Dad.

61
00:03:27,630 --> 00:03:30,040
Truly befitting a great author.

62
00:03:30,710 --> 00:03:34,560
You're like a dinosaur that
actually made it to the modern age.

63
00:03:34,580 --> 00:03:36,640
- Wow.
- Is that a compliment?

64
00:03:36,640 --> 00:03:37,920
It is. Absolutely.

65
00:03:39,020 --> 00:03:41,640
Who'd bad-mouth my Dad, right?

66
00:03:41,640 --> 00:03:45,920
Younger generations are
circling back to old things.

67
00:03:45,950 --> 00:03:48,690
Like film cameras or flip phones.

68
00:03:48,720 --> 00:03:49,140
Hmm?

69
00:03:49,160 --> 00:03:50,680
Coming back into style.

70
00:03:51,110 --> 00:03:54,000
Right, they call it
the nostalgia trend.

71
00:03:54,020 --> 00:03:55,220
- Oh?
- Right, Save?

72
00:03:55,240 --> 00:03:56,370
Something like that.

73
00:03:57,540 --> 00:04:00,280
Eat a lot, everyone.

74
00:04:00,560 --> 00:04:01,940
- Enjoy, enjoy.
- Yes.

75
00:04:01,960 --> 00:04:03,600
Go on, kids.

76
00:04:03,920 --> 00:04:06,440
Hey, this money comes from do...
what again?

77
00:04:06,760 --> 00:04:08,480
- Donations.
- Right.

78
00:04:08,500 --> 00:04:09,480
- Mm-hmm.
- Hmm.

79
00:04:09,500 --> 00:04:11,240
Readers' support for the author.

80
00:04:11,240 --> 00:04:13,240
- Mm-hmm.
- Oh.

81
00:04:13,520 --> 00:04:15,280
Wow, Dad, does that add up to much?

82
00:04:15,520 --> 00:04:17,920
Not a lot, but...
not bad, right?

83
00:04:17,940 --> 00:04:19,890
Enough for this party.

84
00:04:19,910 --> 00:04:22,280
So what about
that paywall thing, Save?

85
00:04:22,310 --> 00:04:24,160
Oh, it's too soon.

86
00:04:24,520 --> 00:04:26,880
- The readership could drop.
- Hmm...

87
00:04:26,910 --> 00:04:30,030
Maybe after 10 chapters.

88
00:04:30,300 --> 00:04:33,640
Heh...Smart.
Sharp business mind.

89
00:04:34,160 --> 00:04:36,560
He's got that from me.

90
00:04:36,580 --> 00:04:37,580
Mm-hmm.

91
00:04:38,400 --> 00:04:41,960
Grandpa, readers are already
asking to buy the book.

92
00:04:42,360 --> 00:04:44,720
If you want a lump sum
to clear the debt fast,

93
00:04:44,850 --> 00:04:46,240
just wrap the story up sooner.

94
00:04:47,120 --> 00:04:49,880
Then you'll have to
work a bit harder.

95
00:04:50,470 --> 00:04:53,840
Keep feeding me the details,
alright?

96
00:04:53,840 --> 00:04:54,840
Of course.

97
00:04:54,860 --> 00:04:56,080
Heh.

98
00:04:56,110 --> 00:04:57,520
No time to waste.

99
00:04:58,150 --> 00:04:59,960
- Cheers...
- Cheers...

100
00:04:59,980 --> 00:05:00,980
I'll join in.

101
00:05:02,610 --> 00:05:03,940
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

102
00:05:04,390 --> 00:05:05,760
Can I join the toast too?

103
00:05:06,370 --> 00:05:07,620
- Hurry, hurry.
- Come, come.

104
00:05:07,640 --> 00:05:09,440
- Let's go.
- Come on.

105
00:05:09,470 --> 00:05:11,200
- Come on.
- Together now.

106
00:05:11,230 --> 00:05:13,800
- Come on.
- Come on.

107
00:05:13,800 --> 00:05:15,910
- Let's toast, everyone.
- Quickly.

108
00:05:15,910 --> 00:05:20,000
Ready. 1, 2, 3, cheers...

109
00:05:20,030 --> 00:05:21,560
- Yay.
- Woo.

110
00:05:26,960 --> 00:05:28,170
Ugh.

111
00:05:29,190 --> 00:05:30,840
Why did I say that?

112
00:05:33,680 --> 00:05:36,560
So you don't want my apology
or to be friends.

113
00:05:37,110 --> 00:05:38,110
Mm-hmm.

114
00:05:46,920 --> 00:05:49,480
"Where are you? Pheem said
you're heading to America."

115
00:05:58,300 --> 00:05:59,400
Phi Save.

116
00:05:59,970 --> 00:06:00,970
Hmm?

117
00:06:01,210 --> 00:06:03,230
- Look here.
- What?

118
00:06:04,110 --> 00:06:08,120
- Looks just like you.
- I'm not playing. Get out.

119
00:06:08,140 --> 00:06:09,880
- Hey.
- Go. Out. Now.

120
00:06:12,110 --> 00:06:13,110
Huh.

121
00:06:14,900 --> 00:06:16,840
- "Messages Read."
- Hey.

122
00:06:17,840 --> 00:06:18,840
Ugh.

123
00:06:20,040 --> 00:06:21,840
"Golden Pen Award"

124
00:06:31,870 --> 00:06:34,210
"Principal and interest:
12,508,649.75 baht."

125
00:06:52,010 --> 00:06:53,800
"You're such a talented writer."

126
00:06:53,800 --> 00:06:55,760
"I'll love this novel forever."

127
00:06:56,840 --> 00:06:59,850
"It makes me
want to get up every morning."

128
00:07:22,980 --> 00:07:24,420
"8"

129
00:07:55,810 --> 00:07:57,640
"Sorry, wrong send."

130
00:07:58,340 --> 00:07:59,340
Ugh.

131
00:08:01,330 --> 00:08:03,240
"Email Inbox: Honey Cheese Pie"

132
00:08:07,920 --> 00:08:08,920
Hey.

133
00:08:11,460 --> 00:08:12,460
Grandpa.

134
00:08:16,480 --> 00:08:17,480
Who is it?

135
00:08:17,510 --> 00:08:18,800
- Grandpa.
- Oh.

136
00:08:22,690 --> 00:08:23,920
- Grandpa.
- Hmm?

137
00:08:24,500 --> 00:08:26,160
You're going viral with Gen Z.

138
00:08:27,060 --> 00:08:28,560
Someone wants to interview you.

139
00:08:29,600 --> 00:08:30,600
Who?

140
00:08:30,630 --> 00:08:31,960
The Y for Life channel.

141
00:08:31,960 --> 00:08:34,520
They're huge
with 200,000 followers.

142
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:37,000
Is that a good thing?

143
00:08:37,410 --> 00:08:39,350
Very much so. Wow.

144
00:08:39,370 --> 00:08:42,790
If people see a retired grandpa
writing BL novels,

145
00:08:43,560 --> 00:08:45,480
- it'll go viral for sure.
- Heh.

146
00:08:45,510 --> 00:08:46,670
Viral?

147
00:08:47,230 --> 00:08:52,160
Because they find it funny
that some old guy is selling BL?

148
00:08:52,220 --> 00:08:56,290
I'm sure it's not like that.
They'll admire you.

149
00:08:56,570 --> 00:08:57,570
Well...

150
00:08:58,820 --> 00:09:01,830
Do you think my longtime readers

151
00:09:01,900 --> 00:09:05,240
can handle me
writing this kind of story now?

152
00:09:05,480 --> 00:09:09,040
Oh-ho. Those old readers
must have dipped by now.

153
00:09:11,080 --> 00:09:13,600
I mean...left this world.

154
00:09:16,470 --> 00:09:18,280
Though my writer friends...

155
00:09:18,700 --> 00:09:20,700
quite a few of them
are still kicking.

156
00:09:21,090 --> 00:09:23,770
- Your men-only literary circle?
- Mm-hmm.

157
00:09:23,770 --> 00:09:24,800
Don't worry about them.

158
00:09:24,820 --> 00:09:28,110
I think, at their age,
they've probably moved on.

159
00:09:29,520 --> 00:09:32,460
Seriously though, Grandpa,
do the interview.

160
00:09:32,940 --> 00:09:34,680
They'll help promote the novel.

161
00:09:35,620 --> 00:09:37,200
Alright, give it a shot.

162
00:09:37,480 --> 00:09:38,480
Really, Grandpa?

163
00:09:38,950 --> 00:09:41,560
Okay, I'll confirm right away.

164
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:44,280
- Is that okay?
- Go ahead.

165
00:10:05,720 --> 00:10:06,800
Yeah, come in.

166
00:10:07,480 --> 00:10:09,200
Wow.

167
00:10:10,230 --> 00:10:13,320
Looking sharp, Grandpa.

168
00:10:15,280 --> 00:10:16,280
Here, let me do that.

169
00:10:16,880 --> 00:10:18,280
Back in the day,

170
00:10:18,800 --> 00:10:21,920
I looked every bit the leading man
of a BL series today.

171
00:10:21,950 --> 00:10:23,400
Mm-hmm.

172
00:10:23,720 --> 00:10:24,720
Hmm.

173
00:10:26,750 --> 00:10:27,840
Alright, done.

174
00:10:30,160 --> 00:10:33,080
Grandpa, no need for that.
Not exactly a lot of hair.

175
00:10:33,800 --> 00:10:35,570
Wait till you're old.

176
00:10:35,760 --> 00:10:39,250
Then you'll know
this is a full head of hair.

177
00:10:41,270 --> 00:10:42,330
Here, hold on.

178
00:10:43,570 --> 00:10:44,570
Okay.

179
00:10:46,440 --> 00:10:47,440
Okay.

180
00:10:51,490 --> 00:10:52,490
Hey.

181
00:10:54,360 --> 00:10:56,840
Grandpa, the interviewer's
almost here.

182
00:11:05,360 --> 00:11:08,180
Hey, Mart, do I look good?

183
00:11:10,020 --> 00:11:14,240
Wow...my heart races
like when we first got together.

184
00:11:14,800 --> 00:11:18,460
- Hmm. You look good too.
- Do I?

185
00:11:18,730 --> 00:11:22,200
Whoo...look at you all dressed up.

186
00:11:22,230 --> 00:11:24,120
- How do I look?
- Oh, wow.

187
00:11:25,520 --> 00:11:28,320
- Wow, Mom.
- Heh.

188
00:11:28,830 --> 00:11:32,400
Well, it's not every day
we have guests over.

189
00:11:32,470 --> 00:11:34,400
Got to make them feel welcome.

190
00:11:34,400 --> 00:11:36,920
Right. And Grandpa?

191
00:11:37,240 --> 00:11:38,440
Getting ready upstairs.

192
00:11:38,800 --> 00:11:41,920
Apparently, his last interview
was twenty years ago.

193
00:11:42,290 --> 00:11:43,660
He's steadying himself.

194
00:11:43,750 --> 00:11:45,800
- Oh.
- Heh.

195
00:11:47,290 --> 00:11:49,440
Quite handsome.

196
00:11:53,100 --> 00:11:58,840
Ho...ha...hoo...wha...

197
00:12:00,160 --> 00:12:01,800
My inspiration, you ask?

198
00:12:03,120 --> 00:12:07,520
I'd say it came from
my time in the military.

199
00:12:19,950 --> 00:12:22,010
"Worachai,
Thailand Writers' Association"

200
00:12:27,760 --> 00:12:31,320
Worachai, how have you been?
It's been a while.

201
00:12:31,720 --> 00:12:33,920
I'm well, Sak. And you?

202
00:12:34,720 --> 00:12:36,060
Can't complain.

203
00:12:36,360 --> 00:12:39,920
Calling about the association,
I presume?

204
00:12:40,310 --> 00:12:42,800
No. I'm calling to let you know

205
00:12:43,360 --> 00:12:46,880
there's a new writer
who's been lifting your work.

206
00:12:47,130 --> 00:12:48,350
Lifting my work?

207
00:12:49,490 --> 00:12:50,720
What do you mean?

208
00:12:50,840 --> 00:12:52,160
I'll send you the thread.

209
00:12:54,900 --> 00:12:56,600
"People are drawing comparisons."

210
00:12:57,020 --> 00:13:01,160
"Some passages in the novel
read suspiciously similar."

211
00:13:01,520 --> 00:13:03,160
"But the most glaring case is..."

212
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:07,400
"Attention: Harn Chanprai,
someone has copied your work."

213
00:13:07,680 --> 00:13:09,960
"There's a hunter character
named Sin."

214
00:13:10,360 --> 00:13:13,800
"Same name, same personality traits"

215
00:13:13,800 --> 00:13:15,520
"as the hunter Sin"

216
00:13:15,520 --> 00:13:19,200
"in your novel
'Braving the Invincible.'"

217
00:13:20,950 --> 00:13:24,440
"Several phrases are clearly lifted
straight from your book."

218
00:13:24,650 --> 00:13:26,980
"The only difference is
it's more transgressive"

219
00:13:27,010 --> 00:13:28,830
"than typical teen romance."

220
00:13:28,960 --> 00:13:30,440
"Can this go to court?"

221
00:13:30,440 --> 00:13:34,160
"Quality literature is dragged down
into something trashy."

222
00:13:41,430 --> 00:13:44,400
This way, please. Right this way.

223
00:13:47,960 --> 00:13:49,120
Welcome, welcome.

224
00:13:54,330 --> 00:13:55,330
Come in, come in.

225
00:13:55,550 --> 00:13:56,600
My grandmother.

226
00:13:56,600 --> 00:13:57,880
Hello.

227
00:14:00,010 --> 00:14:01,400
Come on in, welcome.

228
00:14:05,710 --> 00:14:07,640
Here he is, Honey Cheese Pie,

229
00:14:07,640 --> 00:14:10,160
author of "Between Us
and the Deep Forest."

230
00:14:10,640 --> 00:14:12,120
Hello...

231
00:14:18,680 --> 00:14:19,680
Uh...

232
00:14:20,090 --> 00:14:21,720
Wow.

233
00:14:22,490 --> 00:14:25,450
So this is the author?

234
00:14:26,320 --> 00:14:29,640
From your writing, I didn't expect
you to be this young.

235
00:14:29,670 --> 00:14:30,600
Well...

236
00:14:30,600 --> 00:14:32,800
Yes. He's my grandson.

237
00:14:34,140 --> 00:14:35,480
I trained him myself.

238
00:14:36,240 --> 00:14:39,840
Oh, shall we start the interview?

239
00:14:39,890 --> 00:14:41,120
Uh...

240
00:14:43,080 --> 00:14:45,200
Could I use the bathroom first?

241
00:14:45,880 --> 00:14:47,170
I'm a bit nervous.

242
00:14:47,680 --> 00:14:51,080
Please, take your time.
I'll set up the equipment.

243
00:14:51,080 --> 00:14:52,680
- Sure.
- Everyone, come on in.

244
00:14:54,070 --> 00:14:56,120
Grandpa, come with me.

245
00:15:00,320 --> 00:15:02,400
I'll go get some water.

246
00:15:02,690 --> 00:15:03,730
- Thank you.
- Sure.

247
00:15:05,810 --> 00:15:06,810
Hmm?

248
00:15:14,780 --> 00:15:17,520
Grandpa, why did you tell him
I wrote it?

249
00:15:17,550 --> 00:15:20,120
Shh. Keep it down, he'll hear you.

250
00:15:20,750 --> 00:15:21,920
- Dad.
- Shh.

251
00:15:23,320 --> 00:15:26,440
Why did you say he wrote it?

252
00:15:30,240 --> 00:15:31,240
Read this.

253
00:15:34,400 --> 00:15:37,010
"...more transgressive than
typical teen romance."

254
00:15:38,850 --> 00:15:41,360
If word got out that I wrote this,

255
00:15:42,120 --> 00:15:47,520
my peers who look up to me
in the industry

256
00:15:48,320 --> 00:15:49,720
would lose respect for me.

257
00:15:50,570 --> 00:15:53,880
That's their problem.
You don't owe them that.

258
00:15:55,320 --> 00:15:57,400
Easy for you to say, Save.

259
00:15:57,540 --> 00:16:02,480
Over 40 years of writing,
everything I've achieved,

260
00:16:02,930 --> 00:16:05,680
it was built on their support.

261
00:16:06,760 --> 00:16:08,040
I can't stomach the thought

262
00:16:08,880 --> 00:16:12,120
of being boycotted by people
I've been tied to all this time.

263
00:16:13,520 --> 00:16:14,520
Save.

264
00:16:17,750 --> 00:16:18,750
Help me out.

265
00:16:42,970 --> 00:16:45,210
Okay, ready whenever you are.

266
00:16:45,760 --> 00:16:46,760
Great.

267
00:16:47,430 --> 00:16:49,190
Okay, get the camera set up.

268
00:16:49,780 --> 00:16:52,720
Just a second on the camera...

269
00:16:52,720 --> 00:16:54,640
- it'll keep the drama down.
- Excuse me.

270
00:16:55,230 --> 00:16:57,450
I'm nervous.

271
00:16:57,760 --> 00:16:59,420
Could my grandpa sit with me?

272
00:17:01,040 --> 00:17:04,440
Oh, of course.
We're keeping it casual today.

273
00:17:05,210 --> 00:17:06,210
Sure.

274
00:17:13,520 --> 00:17:14,520
Come on in.

275
00:17:21,920 --> 00:17:24,040
Let me just clip on your mic.

276
00:17:24,040 --> 00:17:25,040
Sure.

277
00:17:31,860 --> 00:17:35,000
Everyone, we're here today

278
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:37,000
with the hottest BL novelist
right now.

279
00:17:37,210 --> 00:17:40,390
A fresh voice
with a truly unique style,

280
00:17:40,550 --> 00:17:42,940
"Between Us in the Deep Forest."

281
00:17:43,050 --> 00:17:44,800
Join us now, Honey Cheese Pie.

282
00:17:45,080 --> 00:17:46,520
- Hello.
- Hello.

283
00:17:47,040 --> 00:17:48,160
Tell us about yourself.

284
00:17:48,160 --> 00:17:52,200
Sure. I'm Supawit Prasitphithaya,
or Save.

285
00:17:52,600 --> 00:17:54,880
Pen name Honey Cheese Pie.

286
00:17:55,200 --> 00:17:56,920
First question then.

287
00:17:57,140 --> 00:18:00,680
How many novels have you penned?

288
00:18:02,080 --> 00:18:03,150
Uh...

289
00:18:04,330 --> 00:18:05,480
My first.

290
00:18:05,980 --> 00:18:09,320
First? That's wild.

291
00:18:09,640 --> 00:18:12,400
It reads like a masterpiece
honed over decades.

292
00:18:13,080 --> 00:18:14,600
Uh...thanks.

293
00:18:14,600 --> 00:18:17,040
Okay, next question.

294
00:18:17,040 --> 00:18:21,520
Inspiration?
Why adventure in the jungle?

295
00:18:21,820 --> 00:18:24,040
- Well...
- I used to be a soldier, you see.

296
00:18:24,560 --> 00:18:29,920
Hard life. Day and night.
Dirt for a bed. Dust for a table.

297
00:18:31,400 --> 00:18:33,330
Plenty of stories to tell.

298
00:18:33,560 --> 00:18:34,560
See...

299
00:18:37,160 --> 00:18:38,310
Ahem.

300
00:18:38,340 --> 00:18:41,490
Anyway, what I mean is...

301
00:18:41,490 --> 00:18:44,760
I told him stories
from my time in the service;

302
00:18:44,760 --> 00:18:49,400
he must've liked them enough
to put them in the novel.

303
00:18:49,430 --> 00:18:54,120
Oh, so you adapted his stories.

304
00:18:54,350 --> 00:18:55,350
That's right.

305
00:18:55,460 --> 00:18:58,560
He's actually a writer himself.

306
00:18:59,110 --> 00:19:01,160
Pen name Harn Chanprai.

307
00:19:01,480 --> 00:19:04,040
- Harn what, sorry?
- Chanprai.

308
00:19:04,500 --> 00:19:06,360
Harn Chanprai.

309
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:10,680
Aw...Harn Chanprai, rings a bell.

310
00:19:10,710 --> 00:19:14,440
So, Save, you are truly
a chip off the old block.

311
00:19:14,540 --> 00:19:15,720
Very much so.

312
00:19:17,330 --> 00:19:19,200
Um...that really is admirable

313
00:19:19,200 --> 00:19:22,760
how a young man like you takes after

314
00:19:22,760 --> 00:19:25,120
your grandpa's prose.

315
00:19:25,120 --> 00:19:26,840
The sky's the limit for you.

316
00:19:26,840 --> 00:19:30,920
Was it a good idea telling him
I'm the grandfather?

317
00:19:31,840 --> 00:19:35,000
He'd just search the surname anyway.

318
00:19:35,150 --> 00:19:36,840
He'd figure it out.

319
00:19:38,720 --> 00:19:42,080
And now that we've lied to him,
won't it cause any damage?

320
00:19:42,390 --> 00:19:43,540
It shouldn't...

321
00:19:44,970 --> 00:19:46,080
- Hopefully.
- Hmm?

322
00:19:51,200 --> 00:19:53,920
Anyway, just ignore
those troll comments.

323
00:19:54,200 --> 00:19:55,920
They're not helping us pay our debt.

324
00:19:56,640 --> 00:19:59,880
Hmm...Save. Those trolls...

325
00:20:00,600 --> 00:20:05,360
They've been my comrades,
fighting alongside me...

326
00:20:05,360 --> 00:20:07,960
from the very beginning
of my writing career.

327
00:20:09,650 --> 00:20:11,120
You couldn't possibly fathom

328
00:20:11,120 --> 00:20:15,080
what I carry as Harn Chanprai.

329
00:20:24,880 --> 00:20:25,880
Okay.

330
00:20:26,700 --> 00:20:29,680
Then Harn's grandson will carry on.

331
00:20:29,880 --> 00:20:30,880
Right.

332
00:20:31,680 --> 00:20:34,160
One interview and that's it.

333
00:20:35,920 --> 00:20:36,920
Save.

334
00:20:39,040 --> 00:20:40,760
Keep it smooth, will you?

335
00:20:40,910 --> 00:20:45,360
Heh...I've got it.
But you, don't slip up again.

336
00:20:58,800 --> 00:21:01,560
"Everyone, we're here today"

337
00:21:01,560 --> 00:21:03,320
"with the hottest BL novelist
right now."

338
00:21:03,460 --> 00:21:05,800
"A fresh voice
with a truly unique style,"

339
00:21:05,830 --> 00:21:09,600
"'Between Us in the Deep Forest.'
Join us now, Honey Cheese Pie."

340
00:21:09,600 --> 00:21:11,840
- "Hello."
- "Tell us about yourself."

341
00:21:12,320 --> 00:21:15,280
"Sure. I'm Supawit Prasitphithaya,
or Save."

342
00:21:15,510 --> 00:21:18,010
"Pen name Honey Cheese Pie."

343
00:21:18,600 --> 00:21:20,280
"First question then."

344
00:21:20,280 --> 00:21:23,920
"How many novels have you penned?"

345
00:21:24,470 --> 00:21:25,600
"My first."

346
00:21:50,440 --> 00:21:53,400
- Heading to the teachers' lounge?
- Since when do you write novels?

347
00:21:54,200 --> 00:21:55,200
What novel?

348
00:21:58,290 --> 00:21:59,480
You saw the interview, huh?

349
00:22:00,040 --> 00:22:01,040
Answer me.

350
00:22:02,380 --> 00:22:06,800
I just started. Just messing around.

351
00:22:07,430 --> 00:22:10,040
Messing around?
You, writing a novel?

352
00:22:10,600 --> 00:22:14,720
Well, I'm the grandson of a writer.
Must be DNA, right?

353
00:22:15,420 --> 00:22:17,360
I read it.
There's no way you wrote that.

354
00:22:17,360 --> 00:22:19,480
Your classwork in
Thai essays was horrendous.

355
00:22:22,680 --> 00:22:25,800
If you can't be honest about this,
what can I trust you with?

356
00:22:27,840 --> 00:22:31,600
Okay. Fine. I didn't write it.

357
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:34,040
Grandpa did.

358
00:22:34,580 --> 00:22:38,040
He just didn't want to put himself
out there, so he had me do it.

359
00:22:42,560 --> 00:22:43,560
Guy.

360
00:22:44,080 --> 00:22:45,760
Wait up, Guy.

361
00:22:49,580 --> 00:22:51,390
- Guy.
- Whoa. Oops.

362
00:22:52,230 --> 00:22:53,280
Watch where you're going.

363
00:22:53,280 --> 00:22:54,440
Sorry.

364
00:22:59,240 --> 00:23:00,400
Anything hurt?

365
00:23:36,300 --> 00:23:39,760
Khun (honorific) Sak, I had no idea
your grandson wrote it.

366
00:23:40,120 --> 00:23:41,680
No worries, Khun Chai.

367
00:23:43,000 --> 00:23:45,840
So what are people talking about
in that thread now?

368
00:23:46,120 --> 00:23:48,920
The plagiarism talk has died down.

369
00:23:49,500 --> 00:23:53,120
But people still compare
your work to your grandson's.

370
00:23:53,820 --> 00:23:56,360
Don't let your grandson read it.

371
00:23:57,080 --> 00:24:00,680
It'll just bring him down.
The comments are toxic.

372
00:24:01,120 --> 00:24:02,480
Understood, Chai.

373
00:24:04,080 --> 00:24:06,240
Thanks for keeping me in the loop.

374
00:24:32,570 --> 00:24:34,560
Are you Phi Honey Cheese Pie?

375
00:24:40,180 --> 00:24:42,640
Uh...yes.

376
00:24:45,400 --> 00:24:48,840
My, my. More handsome in person
than in the clip.

377
00:24:50,520 --> 00:24:51,520
Thanks, guys.

378
00:24:51,850 --> 00:24:56,200
And now, slow new chapters, huh?
I'm dying to read more.

379
00:24:57,920 --> 00:24:58,920
Uh...

380
00:25:00,510 --> 00:25:01,510
I just...

381
00:25:02,240 --> 00:25:03,360
got stuck a bit.

382
00:25:03,680 --> 00:25:07,600
Hang in there.
Both of us are waiting.

383
00:25:09,760 --> 00:25:10,840
Thank you.

384
00:25:11,120 --> 00:25:12,920
Should be the next few days.

385
00:25:13,400 --> 00:25:14,400
Beautiful.

386
00:25:15,360 --> 00:25:16,920
Heh...So handsome.

387
00:25:21,550 --> 00:25:23,600
Hey, you write novels now?

388
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:26,400
Yeah. What's wrong with that?

389
00:25:26,540 --> 00:25:29,720
- Why didn't you tell us?
- Why would I?

390
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:33,760
Hey, I'm still mad at you guys for
lying about Guy going to America.

391
00:25:34,760 --> 00:25:37,590
Oy...I just wanted
you two to make up.

392
00:25:38,050 --> 00:25:40,560
So what's the novel called?
Honey Cheese Pie?

393
00:25:40,690 --> 00:25:41,790
- Hey, you.
- Heh.

394
00:25:41,820 --> 00:25:44,160
- Let me search it.
- Yeah, let's look it up.

395
00:25:46,720 --> 00:25:47,920
Honey Cheese Pie.

396
00:25:50,840 --> 00:25:52,500
- Haha.
- Heh.

397
00:25:52,500 --> 00:25:54,400
Hey, don't tell anyone.

398
00:25:55,420 --> 00:25:56,420
Hey.

399
00:25:56,830 --> 00:25:58,390
Found it, right here.

400
00:25:58,860 --> 00:26:00,670
Hey, don't tell a soul.
I'm outta here.

401
00:26:00,690 --> 00:26:02,000
- Hey.
- Hey.

402
00:26:09,480 --> 00:26:10,480
Grandpa.

403
00:26:12,080 --> 00:26:12,800
Hmm?

404
00:26:12,800 --> 00:26:13,960
- Hello.
- Yeah.

405
00:26:17,880 --> 00:26:20,600
Grandpa, drop the next chapter soon.

406
00:26:20,960 --> 00:26:22,690
The fans are clamoring for it.

407
00:26:23,280 --> 00:26:24,560
Don't rush me.

408
00:26:25,520 --> 00:26:27,440
Writing is a craft.

409
00:26:27,740 --> 00:26:31,800
I don't churn out words
just to fill a quota. Never have.

410
00:26:32,120 --> 00:26:34,640
See, I'm giving you
as much slack as I can.

411
00:26:34,640 --> 00:26:36,760
Honestly, I'd want it
done this week.

412
00:26:37,750 --> 00:26:40,720
This is a novel,
not instant noodles.

413
00:26:40,950 --> 00:26:42,950
Don't ask for the impossible.

414
00:26:43,400 --> 00:26:47,200
Ooy, they say if you sell the book
while it's still trending,

415
00:26:47,530 --> 00:26:49,360
the numbers will
go through the roof.

416
00:26:49,510 --> 00:26:55,030
Heh...normally, each book takes me
a couple of years to finish.

417
00:26:55,710 --> 00:26:59,160
Well, that's not the game now.
It's a race.

418
00:26:59,180 --> 00:27:02,910
Haha. Khun Save,
help me figure out, won't you?

419
00:27:02,910 --> 00:27:06,980
How to finally get these
two characters to make up?

420
00:27:07,140 --> 00:27:09,840
People are complaining
they've been sulking too long.

421
00:27:12,640 --> 00:27:13,640
Well...

422
00:27:14,640 --> 00:27:17,920
Afraid I can't help you.
I still can't get Guy to forgive me.

423
00:27:20,200 --> 00:27:22,520
Then I guess I'm stumped;

424
00:27:23,000 --> 00:27:24,400
the two of them in real life

425
00:27:24,950 --> 00:27:26,870
can't even make up.

426
00:27:28,800 --> 00:27:32,200
Hmm. Fair enough.

427
00:27:33,080 --> 00:27:36,360
But readers are hooked right now.

428
00:27:36,640 --> 00:27:40,360
If they wait too long,
they could go read something else.

429
00:27:41,200 --> 00:27:42,200
Hmm?

430
00:28:07,480 --> 00:28:08,480
Grandpa.

431
00:28:09,040 --> 00:28:10,520
I want to read the next chapter.

432
00:28:11,680 --> 00:28:12,680
Five more days.

433
00:28:13,420 --> 00:28:16,680
Five days?
It's like forever, Grandpa.

434
00:28:17,440 --> 00:28:20,040
You see how many people are asking?

435
00:28:20,540 --> 00:28:21,720
Here are some comments.

436
00:28:22,920 --> 00:28:24,600
Please don't abandon this story.

437
00:28:24,740 --> 00:28:27,880
Come back and finish it.

438
00:28:28,170 --> 00:28:30,970
I'm dying to read more.
It's been dragging on forever.

439
00:28:30,970 --> 00:28:33,120
I give up. Time for something new.

440
00:28:33,750 --> 00:28:36,760
Wait, who's that?
Sounds a little personal.

441
00:28:37,280 --> 00:28:38,840
- It's me, Grandpa.
- Oh.

442
00:28:39,130 --> 00:28:40,280
You'd better post soon.

443
00:28:40,470 --> 00:28:41,470
Heh.

444
00:28:41,770 --> 00:28:43,520
Sure. Posting soon.

445
00:28:44,130 --> 00:28:46,240
Yay. I'll be waiting.

446
00:28:46,410 --> 00:28:47,410
- Good.
- I'm off.

447
00:28:54,080 --> 00:28:55,080
Save.

448
00:28:56,200 --> 00:28:59,600
Save, come help me type.

449
00:29:01,760 --> 00:29:02,760
Okay.

450
00:29:10,230 --> 00:29:11,240
Huh.

451
00:29:34,080 --> 00:29:35,240
You see this?

452
00:29:35,740 --> 00:29:39,760
"Nunan: New chapter, a trainwreck.
Promotes male chauvinism now?"

453
00:29:40,080 --> 00:29:42,800
"Young writer with this ideology?
So disappointed."

454
00:29:42,800 --> 00:29:44,280
"Rakpleple: Real man wrote it."

455
00:29:45,040 --> 00:29:49,770
"aomaom: Forget this.
No gender oppression."

456
00:29:50,930 --> 00:29:51,930
Wow.

457
00:29:57,260 --> 00:29:58,440
Huh.

458
00:30:02,260 --> 00:30:04,720
Grandpa, I say it has to be fixed.

459
00:30:06,080 --> 00:30:07,400
Partly my fault too.

460
00:30:07,840 --> 00:30:12,080
Yesterday, I used a doc scanner app
to convert everything to text.

461
00:30:12,520 --> 00:30:15,920
I fixed the typos
and didn't read it carefully.

462
00:30:16,580 --> 00:30:18,040
How bad could it be?

463
00:30:18,560 --> 00:30:21,510
Hmm. See. People are ranting
to Mom and Dad

464
00:30:21,520 --> 00:30:23,410
and dragging you into it too.

465
00:30:23,560 --> 00:30:27,470
Wait, can we take screenshots
and report them?

466
00:30:27,470 --> 00:30:29,200
Easy, Phi Sorn.

467
00:30:30,320 --> 00:30:31,480
What is wrong with people?

468
00:30:31,710 --> 00:30:36,150
Trashing complete strangers.
How rude.

469
00:30:36,760 --> 00:30:41,920
Back in my day,
someone with real expertise

470
00:30:41,950 --> 00:30:43,930
would critique the work properly,

471
00:30:44,030 --> 00:30:47,960
then publish it in
a reputable newspaper or magazine.

472
00:30:48,200 --> 00:30:49,550
Fair and square.

473
00:30:49,550 --> 00:30:50,550
- Mm-hmm.
- Hmm.

474
00:30:52,200 --> 00:30:53,960
The internet gives everyone
a voice now.

475
00:30:54,760 --> 00:30:56,840
But if you strip away the language,

476
00:30:57,120 --> 00:30:59,720
the point they're making
isn't entirely wrong.

477
00:31:00,040 --> 00:31:03,960
Like how? What did I write
that was out of line?

478
00:31:04,190 --> 00:31:05,190
Mm-hmm.

479
00:31:08,190 --> 00:31:10,960
Confess. Did you steal our supplies?

480
00:31:12,510 --> 00:31:13,510
Ree.

481
00:31:13,720 --> 00:31:15,280
You are quite beautiful, actually.

482
00:31:16,050 --> 00:31:18,040
But you can't keep snarling
like a wild animal.

483
00:31:18,040 --> 00:31:19,320
Raah. Grr.

484
00:31:19,550 --> 00:31:21,520
Try being a little softer.
A little sweeter.

485
00:31:21,660 --> 00:31:23,320
You'd be far more lovely.

486
00:31:23,570 --> 00:31:24,600
Grr.

487
00:31:24,620 --> 00:31:26,320
All that rage

488
00:31:27,080 --> 00:31:29,840
must come from being hurt
by a bad man before.

489
00:31:30,800 --> 00:31:32,000
Truly, it's sad.

490
00:31:32,720 --> 00:31:34,240
Like I always say,

491
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:36,880
if you want to get to
her softer side,

492
00:31:37,440 --> 00:31:39,240
just treat her right

493
00:31:40,280 --> 00:31:41,430
like a real man should.

494
00:31:47,560 --> 00:31:49,120
We mean you no harm.

495
00:31:49,400 --> 00:31:53,480
You want food? Ask nicely.
We'll give it to you.

496
00:32:00,880 --> 00:32:02,400
Let us take care of you, Mali.

497
00:32:02,920 --> 00:32:06,240
It's a gentleman's duty
toward a woman.

498
00:32:09,720 --> 00:32:11,680
See? What's wrong with that?

499
00:32:12,240 --> 00:32:14,800
I wrote a man protecting a woman

500
00:32:15,200 --> 00:32:18,480
because she is something beautiful
and worth cherishing.

501
00:32:18,920 --> 00:32:20,200
Exactly.

502
00:32:20,200 --> 00:32:23,120
And he didn't write
anything aggressive.

503
00:32:23,120 --> 00:32:25,720
No forced kiss
or anything like that.

504
00:32:26,640 --> 00:32:28,920
See? I knew you wouldn't get it.

505
00:32:30,000 --> 00:32:32,480
It seems perfectly fine,
doesn't it?

506
00:32:32,480 --> 00:32:35,480
But there's some
underlying gender bias here.

507
00:32:40,420 --> 00:32:41,920
A few red flags.

508
00:32:42,800 --> 00:32:43,900
Point one,

509
00:32:44,720 --> 00:32:47,720
women today don't need men
to protect them.

510
00:32:49,320 --> 00:32:52,560
Two, the female feral character

511
00:32:53,060 --> 00:32:57,280
is written as savage and raw,
more beast than person.

512
00:32:57,860 --> 00:32:58,860
Hmm?

513
00:32:59,680 --> 00:33:00,880
And point three,

514
00:33:00,880 --> 00:33:03,880
women don't have to be
girly and sweet all the time.

515
00:33:04,230 --> 00:33:08,080
Hmm. When he puts it that way,
it does hold up.

516
00:33:08,080 --> 00:33:09,080
- Mm-hmm.
- Hmm.

517
00:33:09,180 --> 00:33:10,860
Snow, you read it. Any thoughts?

518
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:13,760
Why does a woman
have to start being nice

519
00:33:13,760 --> 00:33:15,960
only after a man
treats her well?

520
00:33:16,560 --> 00:33:18,160
Can't she be that way on her own?

521
00:33:18,720 --> 00:33:22,200
Or maybe her temper has
nothing to do with the man?

522
00:33:22,600 --> 00:33:25,480
I mean, men should be decent
to women regardless.

523
00:33:25,930 --> 00:33:26,980
- Mm-hmm.
- Hmm.

524
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:31,000
And why must women be gentle
and men be strong?

525
00:33:31,110 --> 00:33:34,560
Can't women be strong
and men be gentle?

526
00:33:35,200 --> 00:33:38,160
Or just have both in one person?

527
00:33:38,180 --> 00:33:39,420
- Mm-hmm.
- Hmm.

528
00:33:41,800 --> 00:33:43,120
If I were Mali, Grandpa,

529
00:33:43,400 --> 00:33:45,610
I'd carry a knife for self-defense.

530
00:33:45,710 --> 00:33:47,000
Not get caught so easily.

531
00:33:47,000 --> 00:33:48,760
Mm-hmm.

532
00:33:49,240 --> 00:33:51,360
Snow, I know

533
00:33:51,900 --> 00:33:55,360
there are strong, capable women
like you're describing.

534
00:33:55,680 --> 00:33:59,280
But this character
thinks differently.

535
00:33:59,520 --> 00:34:01,760
And that's exactly
what readers are questioning.

536
00:34:02,040 --> 00:34:04,680
The character's view
or the author's.

537
00:34:07,960 --> 00:34:12,320
Grandpa, it has to be fixed,
or they'll stop reading.

538
00:34:19,510 --> 00:34:22,600
What? Phi Sorn didn't record
ten orders?

539
00:34:22,960 --> 00:34:26,040
Yes, and we don't have
enough ingredients.

540
00:34:26,550 --> 00:34:29,550
Looks like we'll have to
delay the delivery.

541
00:34:35,160 --> 00:34:37,280
Okay, I'll handle it.

542
00:34:38,480 --> 00:34:41,080
But...don't say anything to him.

543
00:34:41,550 --> 00:34:42,550
Of course.

544
00:34:52,530 --> 00:34:54,480
Why the long face?

545
00:34:55,120 --> 00:34:57,800
Oh, nothing, Dad.

546
00:34:58,240 --> 00:35:00,720
Just a small stock issue.

547
00:35:06,560 --> 00:35:09,680
Tell me right now. What's going on?

548
00:35:10,000 --> 00:35:12,840
Nothing at all. Really, nothing.

549
00:35:13,680 --> 00:35:15,440
Don't lie to me. Out with it.

550
00:35:18,840 --> 00:35:22,220
Uh, please don't tell her
I told you.

551
00:35:22,840 --> 00:35:25,880
Khun Sorn failed to
write down ten orders.

552
00:35:26,200 --> 00:35:29,560
Khun Mart is sorting it out
with the customers now.

553
00:35:30,120 --> 00:35:31,280
Him again.

554
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:34,760
Always making a mess
for her to clean up.

555
00:35:45,320 --> 00:35:47,040
Stop reading.
It'll just drag you down.

556
00:35:48,520 --> 00:35:50,840
Those people don't know you
the way I do.

557
00:35:53,060 --> 00:35:54,520
Don't let it get to you. Okay?

558
00:35:55,160 --> 00:35:57,960
Hey, are you...worried about me?

559
00:35:58,900 --> 00:36:01,120
No. I just saw you taking a beating.

560
00:36:01,960 --> 00:36:03,760
Afraid you couldn't handle the fame.

561
00:36:08,470 --> 00:36:09,470
Thanks.

562
00:36:09,960 --> 00:36:11,210
Whatever's wrong, you fix it.

563
00:36:12,320 --> 00:36:14,480
And tell your grandpa
I'm waiting to read more.

564
00:36:17,960 --> 00:36:21,200
You're always so good to me.

565
00:36:27,400 --> 00:36:30,320
So are we...good again?

566
00:36:38,600 --> 00:36:39,600
Here's the deal.

567
00:36:40,800 --> 00:36:43,520
I'll make it up to you by
being your errand boy for a day.

568
00:36:46,520 --> 00:36:47,680
You said it yourself.

569
00:36:47,900 --> 00:36:48,900
Mm-hmm.

570
00:36:55,840 --> 00:36:59,640
- Get it fixed today.
- On it.

571
00:36:59,640 --> 00:37:02,760
Every day, a new problem.
Typical men.

572
00:37:02,760 --> 00:37:04,080
- True.
- Preach.

573
00:37:04,390 --> 00:37:06,870
So annoying.
Look at this half-baked job.

574
00:37:07,870 --> 00:37:09,680
Jingjai, come give us a hand.

575
00:37:13,370 --> 00:37:14,880
One sec. I'm coming.

576
00:37:15,640 --> 00:37:16,880
Okay, come on.

577
00:37:17,870 --> 00:37:18,940
I'm here.

578
00:37:24,640 --> 00:37:26,660
Alright. You hold that. And freeze.

579
00:37:27,160 --> 00:37:28,160
Oh.

580
00:37:29,160 --> 00:37:30,560
Who wrecked the arch?

581
00:37:31,360 --> 00:37:32,560
Yesterday, Grandpa.

582
00:37:32,920 --> 00:37:36,000
Pipe and his boys kicked
a ball right into it.

583
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:40,290
Hmm? They should fix it then.
I'll go get them.

584
00:37:40,290 --> 00:37:41,650
No, Grandpa. It's fine.

585
00:37:41,910 --> 00:37:44,550
We already had them
fix it yesterday.

586
00:37:44,590 --> 00:37:47,320
But it wasn't sturdy at all
and fell apart again.

587
00:37:47,350 --> 00:37:48,670
We'll just do it ourselves.

588
00:37:48,690 --> 00:37:49,750
Hmm.

589
00:37:50,560 --> 00:37:53,480
Can you do it?
Better get the boys over.

590
00:37:54,010 --> 00:37:56,480
We've got it. Just watch.

591
00:37:57,150 --> 00:37:58,150
Let's do it.

592
00:38:12,200 --> 00:38:14,080
I'm so sorry, Khun Sai.

593
00:38:14,430 --> 00:38:15,430
Yes.

594
00:38:20,080 --> 00:38:22,040
I've talked to all the customers.

595
00:38:22,600 --> 00:38:24,920
Heh...well done.

596
00:38:26,050 --> 00:38:27,160
That's my Mart.

597
00:38:27,190 --> 00:38:29,960
Be more careful. No more mistakes.

598
00:38:30,270 --> 00:38:35,270
Of course, I owe you an apology
for all this trouble.

599
00:38:35,500 --> 00:38:38,200
Without you around, I'd be lost.

600
00:38:39,220 --> 00:38:40,340
Of course.

601
00:38:44,470 --> 00:38:47,020
- Oh, Father.
- Yes?

602
00:38:47,040 --> 00:38:49,120
I found a diary.

603
00:38:49,480 --> 00:38:52,110
It's Grandma's
from when she was young.

604
00:38:52,160 --> 00:38:53,650
It was in the storage room.

605
00:38:53,650 --> 00:38:54,840
Have you ever seen it?

606
00:38:55,680 --> 00:38:59,280
I have, but I never read it.

607
00:39:00,240 --> 00:39:03,560
Then take a look.
She wrote about you too.

608
00:39:08,430 --> 00:39:11,380
"Two years since Phi Sombat passed."

609
00:39:11,530 --> 00:39:15,920
"What a shame that he never
got to see little Sak grow up."

610
00:39:16,390 --> 00:39:20,920
"Our boy, at two years old,
is such a dear."

611
00:39:21,360 --> 00:39:24,640
"Today my mind drifted back
to my teaching days."

612
00:39:25,160 --> 00:39:29,520
"Even so, being a mother
fills my heart completely."

613
00:39:30,200 --> 00:39:33,320
"The money from my sewing
and selling sweets"

614
00:39:33,320 --> 00:39:35,720
"is just enough to raise my son."

615
00:39:36,360 --> 00:39:39,360
"I grow tired at times.
I miss you."

616
00:39:39,880 --> 00:39:41,540
"But little Sak's smile"

617
00:39:42,160 --> 00:39:45,440
"always gets me back on my feet
to face another day."

618
00:40:43,680 --> 00:40:46,840
Mom, you must be tired

619
00:40:48,520 --> 00:40:50,960
raising me all on your own.

620
00:41:05,880 --> 00:41:10,600
I never told you
while you could still hear me.

621
00:41:17,240 --> 00:41:18,680
You were the strongest.

622
00:41:49,420 --> 00:41:51,320
Hey, so how did it go?

623
00:41:53,290 --> 00:41:55,280
Did people like the revisions?

624
00:41:58,100 --> 00:41:59,520
They loved it, Grandpa.

625
00:42:01,160 --> 00:42:02,820
They liked what you changed,

626
00:42:03,020 --> 00:42:05,260
and appreciated your
listening to their feedback.

627
00:42:05,640 --> 00:42:07,120
Most writers,

628
00:42:07,140 --> 00:42:09,520
when they get criticized,
don't usually budge.

629
00:42:09,550 --> 00:42:11,890
Hmm. That's a relief.

630
00:42:11,910 --> 00:42:13,150
Heh.

631
00:42:14,690 --> 00:42:18,520
Well done, Grandpa.
Where did you get the idea?

632
00:42:20,920 --> 00:42:23,960
Confess. Did you steal our supplies?

633
00:42:24,120 --> 00:42:25,240
I didn't steal anything.

634
00:42:28,200 --> 00:42:29,840
I was going to trade for them.

635
00:42:31,280 --> 00:42:32,760
Then why not just ask?

636
00:42:33,520 --> 00:42:35,660
If you'd asked,
I would have given them freely.

637
00:42:35,800 --> 00:42:36,960
You weren't here.

638
00:42:37,320 --> 00:42:39,760
I needed to get food back home.

639
00:42:40,240 --> 00:42:41,240
To feed my child.

640
00:42:41,290 --> 00:42:43,900
A child. You have a child?

641
00:42:45,980 --> 00:42:48,540
The idea came from
what's in front of me every day.

642
00:42:48,900 --> 00:42:51,360
I just...never thought to look.

643
00:42:52,640 --> 00:42:55,990
Save, I owe you an apology.

644
00:42:56,620 --> 00:42:58,880
For all the heat
you took on my behalf.

645
00:43:00,160 --> 00:43:01,480
Don't worry about it.

646
00:43:02,720 --> 00:43:06,640
Actually, I have an idea to get
the characters back together.

647
00:43:06,880 --> 00:43:07,880
- Really?
- Mm-hmm.

648
00:43:08,070 --> 00:43:09,140
How?

649
00:43:09,430 --> 00:43:11,720
Something heavy needs to
hit them first.

650
00:43:11,740 --> 00:43:12,740
Mm-hmm.

651
00:43:12,980 --> 00:43:16,840
When the worry runs deep enough,
when the bond is strong enough,

652
00:43:16,840 --> 00:43:18,430
they'll always find their way back.

653
00:43:23,260 --> 00:43:24,560
Ugh.

654
00:43:24,850 --> 00:43:25,850
Ow.

655
00:43:26,870 --> 00:43:27,870
Bear with it.

656
00:43:31,950 --> 00:43:32,950
Ow.

657
00:43:36,890 --> 00:43:37,930
Sit down.

658
00:43:42,300 --> 00:43:43,300
Ugh.

659
00:43:45,040 --> 00:43:47,560
Just a little longer.
Mali's village is just ahead.

660
00:43:48,600 --> 00:43:50,010
So you're talking to me again?

661
00:43:51,320 --> 00:43:53,720
You're about to die
and you're still bringing this up?

662
00:43:56,920 --> 00:43:58,130
If I go now,

663
00:43:59,020 --> 00:44:00,460
at least I'll go in peace.

664
00:44:00,630 --> 00:44:03,200
You are not dying. I won't allow it.

665
00:44:03,960 --> 00:44:07,080
So are we...good again?

666
00:44:09,570 --> 00:44:10,570
Mm-hmm.

667
00:44:25,280 --> 00:44:26,280
Save.

668
00:44:26,840 --> 00:44:29,560
Word is a major channel
wants to do another interview.

669
00:44:29,810 --> 00:44:33,920
Yeah, the drama from last time
only got more people talking.

670
00:44:34,560 --> 00:44:35,760
What should we do?

671
00:44:36,480 --> 00:44:39,920
Go for it, Grandpa.
It'll push the novel even further.

672
00:44:40,240 --> 00:44:43,480
The last interview alone
bumped the numbers way up.

673
00:44:43,790 --> 00:44:45,680
And we only posted on a niche page.

674
00:44:46,200 --> 00:44:48,200
Imagine what a major outlet
could do.

675
00:44:49,040 --> 00:44:50,760
Alright, let's do it.

676
00:44:51,890 --> 00:44:54,670
But...make this the last one.

677
00:44:55,310 --> 00:44:59,080
I don't want to see you
lie to the press anymore.

678
00:44:59,680 --> 00:45:02,840
Mm-hmm. This time they've sent
sample questions ahead.

679
00:45:03,260 --> 00:45:06,920
Good. This time you rehearse.

680
00:45:07,400 --> 00:45:08,400
Yes.

681
00:45:10,760 --> 00:45:12,880
- They'll definitely ask you.
- Mm-hmm.

682
00:45:13,260 --> 00:45:16,000
Is this novel hard to write?

683
00:45:17,480 --> 00:45:19,030
- Hard.
- Because?

684
00:45:19,870 --> 00:45:23,760
Because the...
relationship between the characters?

685
00:45:25,080 --> 00:45:26,800
Like the way it has to

686
00:45:27,980 --> 00:45:29,690
develop so gradually, right?

687
00:45:29,990 --> 00:45:30,990
Mm-hmm.

688
00:46:28,120 --> 00:46:30,080
The relationship
between Somporn and Anan

689
00:46:30,290 --> 00:46:31,600
is like forest vines.

690
00:46:31,870 --> 00:46:35,560
They cinch as they twine,
harder to let go.

691
00:46:36,510 --> 00:46:38,080
That covers
all the scripted questions.

692
00:46:38,080 --> 00:46:40,000
Mind if I throw in a few extra?

693
00:46:40,670 --> 00:46:42,280
Uh, off-script too?

694
00:46:42,550 --> 00:46:43,550
Is that alright?

695
00:46:47,310 --> 00:46:48,800
Sure, go ahead.

696
00:46:50,280 --> 00:46:55,200
Is the forest, in any shape or form,
a symbol of their relationship?

697
00:46:58,160 --> 00:46:59,720
Uh, yes.

698
00:47:02,090 --> 00:47:05,560
Excuse me. I need to
use the bathroom for a second.

699
00:47:05,590 --> 00:47:06,710
Be back with the answer.

700
00:47:06,710 --> 00:47:08,320
Oh, of course. Go right ahead.

701
00:47:18,670 --> 00:47:22,760
I think the forest reflects
a kind of truth about life.

702
00:47:24,120 --> 00:47:26,920
People get lost
because they can't see the way.

703
00:47:27,560 --> 00:47:30,830
But sometimes it's us
who don't want to see the way.

704
00:47:34,040 --> 00:47:35,720
Beautifully put, Save.

705
00:47:35,720 --> 00:47:38,240
And how do you create
romantic scenes?

706
00:47:38,240 --> 00:47:40,120
Reading them,
I can't stop smiling.

707
00:47:44,760 --> 00:47:46,280
- Uh, excuse me.
- Yes.

708
00:47:46,730 --> 00:47:49,440
Give me a minute to change
Great-grandma's diaper, okay?

709
00:47:50,130 --> 00:47:51,050
Uh, sure.

710
00:47:51,080 --> 00:47:53,320
- I'll be right back.
- Of course, go ahead.

711
00:48:05,070 --> 00:48:06,840
I'm drawn to the small things.

712
00:48:07,010 --> 00:48:10,280
Like sharing
the last bite of something.

713
00:48:10,680 --> 00:48:13,960
Or leaning against each other
when the rain comes down.

714
00:48:16,060 --> 00:48:17,670
Nothing too romantic.

715
00:48:18,860 --> 00:48:20,410
But still makes your heart race.

716
00:48:21,840 --> 00:48:24,560
And before these two characters
entered the forest,

717
00:48:24,590 --> 00:48:26,080
what were their lives like?

718
00:48:30,000 --> 00:48:33,960
Uh, that one
I can't answer just yet.

719
00:48:34,840 --> 00:48:36,920
It might come up in the future.

720
00:48:37,790 --> 00:48:40,830
It'd be a big spoiler
to reveal it now.

721
00:48:41,260 --> 00:48:43,510
Oh, fair enough.

722
00:48:44,690 --> 00:48:47,120
Well then,
let's talk a little about you.

723
00:48:47,670 --> 00:48:48,670
Go right ahead.

724
00:48:54,440 --> 00:48:58,670
"Between Us and the Forest,
Chapter 8"

725
00:49:04,490 --> 00:49:07,560
You just mentioned some parts
came from real experience.

726
00:49:07,900 --> 00:49:09,840
Can I ask a personal question?

727
00:49:10,480 --> 00:49:11,760
Do you have a boyfriend?

728
00:49:15,720 --> 00:49:18,440
Well...not quite at that stage yet.

729
00:49:19,110 --> 00:49:21,110
We're just talking, really.

730
00:49:23,420 --> 00:49:24,420
Right.

731
00:49:34,920 --> 00:49:36,160
"Do you have a boyfriend?"

732
00:49:36,190 --> 00:49:37,560
"Not quite at that stage yet."

733
00:49:38,320 --> 00:49:40,150
"We're just talking, really."

734
00:49:41,470 --> 00:49:43,200
"Could you bring him on?"

735
00:49:43,960 --> 00:49:45,640
"I'll ask him."

736
00:50:00,600 --> 00:50:01,890
"Phuri"

737
00:50:05,280 --> 00:50:06,280
Hello.

738
00:50:06,310 --> 00:50:08,920
Hello, sir. How are you?
How have you been?

739
00:50:09,280 --> 00:50:11,480
Not great, actually.

740
00:50:12,040 --> 00:50:15,360
Been hunched over
writing this novel.

741
00:50:15,360 --> 00:50:18,320
The one you said wouldn't sell.

742
00:50:18,350 --> 00:50:20,240
Well, sir.

743
00:50:20,420 --> 00:50:23,140
I clearly had eyes but no vision.

744
00:50:23,660 --> 00:50:25,800
I've read all the chapters so far.

745
00:50:26,200 --> 00:50:29,280
It's a genuinely
remarkable BL novel.

746
00:50:29,640 --> 00:50:32,520
So I'd like to be
the one to publish it.

747
00:50:32,960 --> 00:50:35,290
Let me think it over first.

748
00:50:35,760 --> 00:50:39,760
See, now. Several publishers have
already reached out,

749
00:50:40,120 --> 00:50:43,680
and I haven't decided
who to go with yet.

750
00:50:43,700 --> 00:50:46,760
- Heh.
- No rush, sir. Take your time.

751
00:50:47,480 --> 00:50:49,680
Just keep me in mind, please.

752
00:50:50,050 --> 00:50:53,200
Your novels have been
with our house for decades,

753
00:50:53,200 --> 00:50:55,080
going back to my father's time.

754
00:50:55,400 --> 00:50:56,680
I hope you'll consider us.

755
00:50:57,580 --> 00:51:02,000
I'll give it some thought.
Is that everything?

756
00:51:02,330 --> 00:51:04,080
Oh, one more thing, sir.

757
00:51:04,570 --> 00:51:07,360
I caught the interview
on the Y for Life page.

758
00:51:07,360 --> 00:51:10,480
Why did you let your grandson
front as the author?

759
00:51:19,170 --> 00:51:21,400
Hey. I'm here, as promised.

760
00:51:21,920 --> 00:51:24,720
Your personal errand boy
for the day. Whatever you need.

761
00:51:28,440 --> 00:51:29,440
What's wrong?

762
00:51:30,680 --> 00:51:32,040
Are you putting me on a show?

763
00:51:32,600 --> 00:51:33,760
You saw the interview?

764
00:51:36,160 --> 00:51:37,760
Using me to boost your fame,
is that it?

765
00:51:38,080 --> 00:51:40,600
No. You've got it wrong.

766
00:51:41,170 --> 00:51:43,770
Trust me, Save.
Bring your guy on together.

767
00:51:44,440 --> 00:51:45,840
He's not my guy, sir.

768
00:51:46,440 --> 00:51:49,280
And he's shy.
Not comfortable on camera.

769
00:51:50,400 --> 00:51:54,000
But if you bring him on my show,
my views go up

770
00:51:54,120 --> 00:51:55,920
and your novel's readership follows.

771
00:51:59,080 --> 00:52:00,480
He wouldn't like to come on.

772
00:52:03,370 --> 00:52:04,530
I already told them no.

773
00:52:05,000 --> 00:52:07,960
You know, ever since I found out
about your novel,

774
00:52:08,490 --> 00:52:10,840
I could piece together
why you kept coming around me.

775
00:52:13,420 --> 00:52:15,680
I've read the novel
to the latest chapter.

776
00:52:15,810 --> 00:52:17,200
That makeup scene,

777
00:52:17,480 --> 00:52:19,720
you gave your grandfather
everything between us.

778
00:52:20,390 --> 00:52:21,390
Guy.

779
00:52:21,840 --> 00:52:23,520
I've been nothing
but decent to you.

780
00:52:24,240 --> 00:52:26,560
Even after all you did to me.

781
00:52:26,880 --> 00:52:28,720
But was any of it ever real?

782
00:52:49,400 --> 00:52:50,520
Anything hurt?

783
00:53:10,380 --> 00:53:12,680
Let me ask you this.
Do you like him?

784
00:53:15,510 --> 00:53:19,160
If you're clear about
your feelings, don't deny them.

785
00:53:19,690 --> 00:53:20,590
Don't hold back.

786
00:53:20,880 --> 00:53:22,600
If I actually like a guy,

787
00:53:23,650 --> 00:53:24,800
are you okay with that?

788
00:53:25,960 --> 00:53:29,040
Mart, someone just called.
Save has been hit by a car.

789
00:53:29,040 --> 00:53:30,040
- What?
- What?

790
00:53:30,070 --> 00:53:35,920
The world keeps
turning every day.

791
00:53:35,920 --> 00:53:41,160
